<h1><span property="schema:name">Video Examples for Navigating Difficult Conversations</span>
</h1>
</div>
<div id="block-medsites-content" class="widget block">
<article data-history-node-id="2590" role="article" about="/commodorecompendium/video-examples-navigating-difficult-conversations" typeof="schema:WebPage">
<div>
<div property="schema:text" class="field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><div>
<div style="border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt; border-top:double windowtext 1.5pt; border-left:none; border-right:none; padding:1.0pt 0in 1.0pt 0in">
<p style="border:none; padding:0in"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><b><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Video Examples for Navigating Difficult Conversations – Mohana Karlekar</span></span></span></b></span></span></span></p>
</div>
<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Navigating difficult conversations with patients can be daunting especially if you have never seen someone do one well before.  Conversations should follow a logical and sequential approach. much like any procedure we perform in medicine.  Like all procedures, practice makes us better</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p> </p>
<p><b><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="line-height:107%"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Scan the QR Code To View Video Examples Or Search The Learning Exchange “Navigating Difficult Conversations With Patients”</span></span></span></span></b></p>
</div>
<p><img alt="QR Code" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="2c524db5-5c53-4ef3-b775-3b4829476db2" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/QR_Code.png"/></p>
<p> </p>
<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Good communicators have both <b>formulated</b> their message and <b>identified</b> which communication strategy to use before they initiate a conversation</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Here are some suggestions for “Navigating Difficult Conversations”</span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="tab-stops:list 9.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Step 1. Determine your message-keep it simple and short</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="tab-stops:list 9.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Step 2. Identify what type of news you are communicating: breaking bad news, assessing understanding of information, communicating prognosis or navigating goals of care</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="tab-stops:list 9.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino"><span style="color:black">Step 3. Pick the video that best suits your purpose  </span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
</ul>
